sql:
SELECT date, sunspot_number
FROM sunspot_data
ORDER BY date ASC;

SELECT AVG(sunspot_number) AS average_sunspot_number
FROM sunspot_data
WHERE year = 2022;

SELECT year, AVG(sunspot_number) AS average_sunspot_number
FROM sunspot_data
GROUP BY year;

external_knowledge:
- 'last year' refers to the year 2022;
- 'locations of the most active spot observations' corresponds to the latitude where sunspots were observed;
- 'intensity of activity' signifies the sunspot number, which is a measure of solar activity.

sql:
SELECT sunspot_number
FROM sunspot_data
WHERE year = 1749 AND month = 12;

external_knowledge:
- High-quality observations refer to those with a quality score above or equal to 90;
- Higher sunspot numbers indicate more solar activity, often referred to metaphorically as "shining brighter" or being more active, akin to stars in the night sky;
- Averaging sunspot numbers helps in identifying typical solar activity levels per year.
